  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Acts 10:3-6",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Acts 10:3-6",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "He saw ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— At a time, it seems, when engaged in secret devotion; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "in a vision ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Not in a trance, like Peter; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "evidently ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Φανερως",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", manifestly and plainly, so as to leave him, though not accustomed to things of this kind, no room to suspect any imposition; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "about the ninth hour ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— That is, about three in the afternoon, which, being the hour of evening sacrifice, was chosen by him as a proper season for his devotion; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "an angel of God ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Known to be such by the brightness of his countenance and the manner of his coming in to him: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and saying, Cornelius ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Calling him by his name, to intimate the particular notice God took of him. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And when he looked on him ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Ατενισας αυτω",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "having fixed his eyes on him; he was",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "afraid ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— And no wonder, for the wisest and best of men have been struck with fear upon the appearance of any extraordinary messenger from heaven; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and said, What is it, Lord? ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— As if he had said, What can this mean? for the words seem to be a sudden exclamation, and prayer to God to preserve him, and let him know what was the design of so astonishing an appearance. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And he ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(the angel) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "said, Thy prayers, and thine alms ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— With which they have been attended; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "have come up for a memorial before God",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " — Far more pleasing to him than the most fragrant incense. And dare any man say, then, that these were only splendid sins? or that they were an abomination before God? And yet it is certain, in the Christian sense, Cornelius was then an unbeliever. He had not then faith in Christ. So certain it is, that every one who seeks faith in Christ, should seek it in prayer and doing good to all men. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And now ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Adds the angel, since God is about to give thee a very singular proof of his love, by discovering things to thee which it is of the highest importance thou shouldst know; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "send, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "therefore, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "to Joppa, and call for one Simon, &c.; he shall tell thee what thou oughtest to do ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Two things here are remarkable, and worthy of particular attention: 1st, Cornelius is influenced continually by the fear of God; from that principle he prays and gives alms; is religious himself, and maintains religion in his family. And all this he does in such a manner as to be accepted of God therein. Nevertheless, it is now necessary he should do something further; he must embrace the Christian religion, God having now established it among men. Not, he might do this if he pleased, and it would be an improvement of his religion; but, he must do it, his doing it is indispensably necessary to his acceptance with God for the future. He that had believed the promise of the Messiah, must now believe the performance of that promise. Now God having given a further record concerning his Son than what had been given in the Old Testament prophecies, he requires men to receive that record when it is brought to them; and unless they do so, neither their prayers nor their alms can any longer come up for a memorial before him. Prayers and alms are indeed still accepted from those that believe in God and fear him, if they have not an opportunity of knowing more. But with those to whom the gospel is preached, it is necessary, in order to the acceptance of their persons, prayers, and alms, that they should believe that Jesus is the Christ, and should confide in him alone for acceptance. 2d, Though Cornelius has now an angel from heaven talking to him, yet he must not receive the gospel of Christ from this angel, nor be told by him what he ought to do, but must send for Peter to inform him. As the former observation puts a remarkable honour upon the gospel, so doth this upon the gospel ministry. It was not to angels, but to saints, persons compassed about with infirmity, that this grace was given, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "to preach among the Gentiles the unsearchable riches of Christ, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "that the excellence of the power might be of God, and the dignity of Christ’s institution supported. And as it was an honour to the apostle, that he must preach that which an angel might not, so it was a further honour, that an angel was despatched from heaven on purpose to order him to be sent for. Observe, reader, to bring a faithful minister and a willing people together, is a work worthy of an angel, and what, therefore, the greatest of men should be glad to be employed in.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "10:1-8 Hitherto none had been baptized into the Christian church but Jews, Samaritans, and those converts who had been circumcised and observed the ceremonial law; but now the Gentiles were to be called to partake all the privileges of God's people, without first becoming Jews. Pure and undefiled religion is sometimes found where we least expect it. Wherever the fear of God rules in the heart, it will appear both in works of charity and of piety, neither will excuse from the other. Doubtless Cornelius had true faith in God's word, as far as he understood it, though not as yet clear faith in Christ. This was the work of the Spirit of God, through the mediation of Jesus, even before Cornelius knew him, as is the case with us all when we, who before were dead in sin, are made alive. Through Christ also his prayers and alms were accepted, which otherwise would have been rejected. Without dispute or delay Cornelius was obedient to the heavenly vision. In the affairs of our souls, let us not lose time.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "He saw in a vision - See the notes on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 9:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Evidently - Openly; manifestly.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "About the ninth hour - About 3 o'clock p. m. This was the usual hour of evening worship among the Jews.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "An angel of God - See the notes on Matthew 1:20. Compare Hebrews 1:14. This angel was sent to signify to Cornelius that his alms were accepted by God as an evidence of his piety, and to direct him to send for Peter to instruct him in the way of salvation. The importance of the occasion - the introduction of the gospel to a Gentile, and hence, to the entire Gentile world - was probably the chief reason why an angel was commissioned to visit the Roman centurion. Compare Acts 16:9-10. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "An angel of God - See the notes on ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Matthew 1:20",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". Compare ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Hebrews 1:14",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". This angel was sent to signify to Cornelius that his alms were accepted by God as an evidence of his piety, and to direct him to send for Peter to instruct him in the way of salvation. The importance of the occasion - the introduction of the gospel to a Gentile, and hence, to the entire Gentile world - was probably the chief reason why an angel was commissioned to visit the Roman centurion. Compare ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Acts 16:9-10",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
