  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Gill's Exposition of the Entire Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "He saw in a vision evidently,.... He was not in a dream, or in a trance, but he was thoroughly awake, and his eyes open, and was himself; it was not in the night, but in clear day: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "about the ninth hour of the day; or three o'clock in the afternoon, which was the hour of prayer, Acts 3:1 in which exercise he was now engaged, Acts 10:30 at this time he saw ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "about the ninth hour of the day; or three o'clock in the afternoon, which was the hour of prayer, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Acts 3:1",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " in which exercise he was now engaged, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Acts 10:30",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " at this time he saw ",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "an angel of God coming to him; into the room where he was at prayer: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and saying unto him, Cornelius; he called him by his name, to let him know that he knew him, as angels are very knowing spirits; and to express his affection and friendship to him, and that he was a messenger, not of bad, but of good news to him; as well as to engage his attention to him; for he might be so intent at his devotion, that had he not called him by name, he would not have minded him. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "and saying unto him, Cornelius; he called him by his name, to let him know that he knew him, as angels are very knowing spirits; and to express his affection and friendship to him, and that he was a messenger, not of bad, but of good news to him; as well as to engage his attention to him; for he might be so intent at his devotion, that had he not called him by name, he would not have minded him. ",
            "children": []
